```

This correctly forces safe vent when the door is open.

Actually, I just realized something! When we receive DOOR_OPEN, we call force_safe_vent which sets s_controller.compressor_on = false and s_controller.vent_open = true. But then at the end of the function, we have:
```c
// Update output with current controller state
output.compressor_on = s_controller.compressor_on;
output.vent_open = s_controller.vent_open;
output.state = s_controller.state;
```

This copies from s_controller to output, which should be correct since force_safe_vent already updated s_controller.

Wait, I think I see a potential issue! When we call force_safe_vent in the DOOR_OPEN case, we don't return early - we just break out of the switch and continue to the end of the function. Let me check my code:

```c
case CONTROLLER_INPUT_DOOR_OPEN:
    // Update door freshness
    s_controller.has_valid_door = true;
    s_controller.door_closed = false;
    s_controller.last_door_ms = input.now_ms;

    // Door open forces safe vent-open state immediately
    force_safe_vent(&output);
    break;  // Just break, don't return early!
```

So after force_safe_vent, we break and then at the end we copy from s_controller to output. This should be correct because force_safe_vent already updated both s_controller and output.

But wait - after breaking from the switch, we have:
```c
